[SPEAKER_16]: Please give your name and address for the record, please.

172
00:15:52,525 --> 00:15:55,627
[SPEAKER_02]: Uh, Tom Lincoln, uh, 27, uh, Gleason street.

173
00:15:56,316 --> 00:15:59,477
[SPEAKER_02]: I've been following this process the best I can.

174
00:16:00,957 --> 00:16:03,538
[SPEAKER_02]: And I know it's been a long road here.

175
00:16:04,278 --> 00:16:05,178
[SPEAKER_02]: It's my observation.

176
00:16:05,218 --> 00:16:23,143
[SPEAKER_02]: I think a lot of people concerned about this that we're kind of losing the battle on the canopy of trees in Medford in terms of despite the tremendous work that's been done by Aggie and the city, we're behind the eight ball on city shade trees.

177
00:16:23,912 --> 00:16:26,674
[SPEAKER_02]: We still have a large number of stumps.

178
00:16:27,794 --> 00:16:42,463
[SPEAKER_02]: All you have to do is look at, and I think they did some cleanup there, which is good, at the stump dump up near the Brooks Estate to see the volume of trees that have been cut down and moved to that site.

179
00:16:43,323 --> 00:16:48,947
[SPEAKER_02]: So I think that if this is not comprehensive, it's not going to do very much good.

180
00:16:50,332 --> 00:17:18,626
[SPEAKER_02]: The other thing I wanted to raise, wearing another hat here, is that the committee that's been working on the comprehensive plan, if you've looked at the draft there, this is a very high priority item in the draft plan, great public concern about trees, the shade canopy, it's related to issues of open space protection, both on public and private property in Medford.

181
00:17:18,806 --> 00:17:19,527
[SPEAKER_02]: And I think that,

182
00:17:20,933 --> 00:17:21,874
[SPEAKER_02]: it would be very good.

183
00:17:22,674 --> 00:17:35,600
[SPEAKER_02]: We don't yet have the action portion of the comprehensive plan in front of us, but I'm very hopeful with the number of members of the committee that this will be a high priority there.

184
00:17:35,760 --> 00:17:47,666
[SPEAKER_02]: So I think coordinating that in terms of what the comprehensive plan wants to do as a guide in the next 10 to 30 years, believe it or not, is going to be

185
00:17:50,647 --> 00:17:51,728
[SPEAKER_02]: is going to be critical.

186
00:17:52,568 --> 00:18:06,615
[SPEAKER_02]: The last thing I wanted to mention, and forgive me if I don't know where this is in the draft, is that it strikes me and I think other people that there is an issue about the relationship of this to zoning.

187
00:18:07,515 --> 00:18:19,041
[SPEAKER_02]: For example, in terms of the zoning and planning and planning permission, in terms of trees removed, trees being replaced at least one for one or maybe a better ratio than that.

188
00:18:20,037 --> 00:18:25,741
[SPEAKER_02]: the number of trees, which I don't think there's any requirement right now on large parking lots.

189
00:18:26,462 --> 00:18:40,912
[SPEAKER_02]: I think of the place over on the Fells Way, which I go to a lot, you know, these big heat sinks sitting there and, you know, either onsite or compensatory trees.

190
00:18:40,932 --> 00:18:44,735
[SPEAKER_02]: There are many cities in the United States that have good ordinances on that.

191
00:18:45,576 --> 00:18:47,277
[SPEAKER_02]: I think this is a goal.

192
00:18:47,838 --> 00:18:59,384
[SPEAKER_02]: an environmental goal and a climate goal, a mitigation goal, an aesthetic goal for the city and its residents that needs to be met on a whole number of fronts.

193
00:18:59,564 --> 00:19:01,585
[SPEAKER_02]: And there are lots of places for trees.

194
00:19:02,025 --> 00:19:06,987
[SPEAKER_02]: There's lots of places where we can do more, we can do better.

195
00:19:07,007 --> 00:19:15,472
[SPEAKER_02]: We're not going to solve this issue next week or next year, but it's a matter of what the trend is.

196
00:19:17,477 --> 00:19:22,598
[SPEAKER_02]: Unfortunately, we're at a point where we have made progress.

197
00:19:22,758 --> 00:19:32,640
[SPEAKER_02]: I think last year, based on the street tree, I think more trees are planted last year than have been done in a long time, but we're still playing serious catch-up ball here.

198
00:19:32,980 --> 00:19:41,422
[SPEAKER_02]: And certainly on my end of town here in West Medford, we have a lot of very large trees.

199
00:19:41,502 --> 00:19:46,963
[SPEAKER_02]: I don't know much about the carbon picture exactly, but my guess is that a large tree is worth many,

200
00:19:47,703 --> 00:19:52,985
[SPEAKER_02]: many small trees, many two and a half inch caliber trees that I'm always talking about.

201
00:19:54,446 --> 00:20:03,831
[SPEAKER_02]: And, you know, you lose one of those, you know, you're way behind in terms of all the benefits.

202
00:20:04,331 --> 00:20:09,313
[SPEAKER_02]: And I think that, you know, I think we need to do, I think we need to do a lot.

203
00:20:09,413 --> 00:20:12,655
[SPEAKER_02]: I think we need to be thinking short term and long term here.

204
00:20:12,715 --> 00:20:14,836
[SPEAKER_02]: And I think we need the framework for

205
00:20:15,985 --> 00:20:24,445
[SPEAKER_02]: both encouraging people to plant trees, encouraging people to take care of trees, planting more trees, the whole shebang needs to be in there.

206
00:20:24,726 --> 00:20:24,986
[SPEAKER_02]: Thanks.

207
00:20:26,700 --> 00:20:45,113
[SPEAKER_16]: Mr. Lincoln, just relative to the zoning question that was one of the requests that we made at our previous meeting to city solicitor slash legal counsel that when they provide us a new draft, anything that would need to be in a zoning frame versus a general ordinance frame be separated out to its own amendment for zoning.

208
00:20:45,473 --> 00:20:46,074
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay, thanks.

209
00:20:47,520 --> 00:20:51,944
[SPEAKER_16]: I'm going to go to President Morrell and then we do have some members of the public but I'll go to President Morrell first.

210
00:20:52,824 --> 00:20:56,947
[SPEAKER_08]: I'm going to Commissioner McIvern, thank you for being here.

211
00:20:57,168 --> 00:20:58,549
[SPEAKER_08]: Apologies I couldn't be there in person.

212
00:20:59,730 --> 00:21:10,037
[SPEAKER_08]: With regards to and this may dive into the area of legal so I understand if you can't answer but with regards to the private trees I mean is there a separation in your mind as far as you know

213
00:21:11,018 --> 00:21:26,094
[SPEAKER_08]: one or two on a private property, or, you know, a developer buying up a lot and completely clear cutting, you know, a dozen trees kind of thing, as far as like your kind of level of comfort with potential legislation around that.

214
00:21:27,110 --> 00:21:29,692
[SPEAKER_04]: Sure, I can give you my opinion from a land development perspective.

215
00:21:30,632 --> 00:21:31,373
[SPEAKER_04]: That one I know well.

216
00:21:31,753 --> 00:21:40,719
[SPEAKER_04]: So as Mr. Lincoln was alluding to, there's ways to craft site plan regulations that involve landscaping requirements that involve trees.

217
00:21:41,259 --> 00:21:50,905
[SPEAKER_04]: So when you're talking about developers coming in and saying, okay, I'm gonna tear down a couple of houses, maybe join a couple of parcels together, build a bigger building with a parking lot, that could happen.

218
00:21:52,338 --> 00:21:58,923
[SPEAKER_04]: there's ways to do that through site plan review, you know, to sort of help control that and increase plantings.

219
00:22:00,064 --> 00:22:14,937
[SPEAKER_04]: And then, so I'm kind of going to reverse, to touch upon your first statement about private trees in general, you know, obviously I'm not a lawyer, but I do have to work with that set of laws, chapter 87, for example.

220
00:22:15,857 --> 00:22:18,640
[SPEAKER_04]: So my understanding as a commissioner of public works,

221
00:22:19,360 --> 00:22:24,843
[SPEAKER_04]: is that a private tree on private property is private property, part of that land, part of the title of that land.

222
00:22:25,823 --> 00:22:29,145
[SPEAKER_04]: So, you know, there's a whole host of mass general law.

223
00:22:29,185 --> 00:22:45,253
[SPEAKER_04]: And I think Massachusetts is unique in this regard, having to do with private trees and what your neighbors, including municipalities, the people that are in the care and control right away, what we can and can't do to the trees on our neighbor's property.

224
00:22:46,414 --> 00:22:47,815
[SPEAKER_04]: So anyway, hopefully that

225
00:22:49,356 --> 00:22:50,777
[SPEAKER_04]: boils it down for you from my perspective.

226
00:22:52,078 --> 00:22:52,779
[SPEAKER_08]: Great, thank you.

227
00:22:53,499 --> 00:23:05,809
[SPEAKER_08]: And if I could just to Mr. Lincoln's point, we did in the recent zoning update that was passed in March, we did have some performance standards for larger developments that are encouraged.

228
00:23:05,849 --> 00:23:12,534
[SPEAKER_08]: They're not, I believe they don't have to be, but they are looked favorably upon the city if certain approvals are needed.

229
00:23:12,654 --> 00:23:16,237
[SPEAKER_08]: So there is some language like that, and I think it's a starting block.

230
00:23:21,759 --> 00:23:22,920
[SPEAKER_16]: Anything further, President Morrell?

231
00:23:23,600 --> 00:23:24,721
[SPEAKER_08]: That's all I have for now, thank you.

232
00:23:24,741 --> 00:23:26,121
[SPEAKER_16]: Thank you.

233
00:23:27,142 --> 00:23:30,123
[SPEAKER_16]: Any other comments from fellow councilors before I go back to members of the public?

234
00:23:31,804 --> 00:23:34,146
[SPEAKER_16]: We're going to go to Martha Andres.

235
00:23:34,546 --> 00:23:36,287
[SPEAKER_16]: Name and address for the record, please.

236
00:23:37,867 --> 00:23:41,990
[SPEAKER_05]: My, okay, my name is Martha Andres.

237
00:23:42,010 --> 00:23:44,211
[SPEAKER_05]: I live at 45 Kilgore Avenue in Medford.

238
00:23:44,231 --> 00:23:44,251
[SPEAKER_05]: I,

239
00:23:46,920 --> 00:23:56,387
[SPEAKER_05]: I'm concerned about the language that's been used that we would go on to private property if we regulate protection of trees.

240
00:23:56,628 --> 00:24:05,114
[SPEAKER_05]: I think if I put a drain into my sump pump in my basement, the city regulates that.

241
00:24:05,475 --> 00:24:08,417
[SPEAKER_05]: If I add to my house, the city regulates that.

242
00:24:09,862 --> 00:24:13,344
[SPEAKER_05]: If I put a trench drain around my house, the city regulates that.

243
00:24:13,464 --> 00:24:18,766
[SPEAKER_05]: I had never heard any of those regulations called going onto my property.

244
00:24:19,026 --> 00:24:32,612
[SPEAKER_05]: So I honestly don't see why protecting trees is in a separate category in terms of the city's ability to protect the public interest.

245
00:24:32,692 --> 00:24:35,433
[SPEAKER_05]: That tree is probably going to do more for

246
00:24:36,730 --> 00:24:45,216
[SPEAKER_05]: water retention and drainage and shading on my property than a lot of other improvements that the city does regulate.

247
00:24:47,578 --> 00:24:59,546
[SPEAKER_05]: I've also noted that a number of cities and towns in Massachusetts do regulate protection of private trees of a certain size or characteristics.

248
00:24:59,626 --> 00:25:01,748
[SPEAKER_05]: So it's definitely possible

249
00:25:02,557 --> 00:25:05,319
[SPEAKER_05]: to do that within Massachusetts General Laws.

250
00:25:05,680 --> 00:25:08,702
[SPEAKER_05]: So that's my contribution here.

251
00:25:08,762 --> 00:25:09,203
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you.

252
00:25:10,904 --> 00:25:11,525
[SPEAKER_16]: Thank you, Martha.

253
00:25:11,565 --> 00:25:14,487
[SPEAKER_16]: Much appreciated.

254
00:25:14,728 --> 00:25:15,829
[SPEAKER_16]: Go to Barry.

255
00:25:15,849 --> 00:25:18,611
[SPEAKER_16]: Name and address for the record, please.

256
00:25:20,453 --> 00:25:22,634
[SPEAKER_12]: Barry Ingber, 9 Draper Street.

257
00:25:23,255 --> 00:25:29,240
[SPEAKER_12]: And I serve as a member of the Energy and Environment Committee along with Martha.

258
00:25:30,580 --> 00:25:35,904
[SPEAKER_12]: President Morrell, though I am not speaking on behalf of that committee.

259
00:25:35,944 --> 00:25:37,766
[SPEAKER_12]: I'm speaking only on behalf of myself.

260
00:25:38,847 --> 00:25:45,152
[SPEAKER_12]: And I don't know Mr. Lincoln, but I want to applaud everything that both he and Ms.

261
00:25:45,232 --> 00:25:46,553
[SPEAKER_12]: Andrus have said.

262
00:25:48,770 --> 00:25:56,734
[SPEAKER_12]: I have comments about the content of the ordinance that I am not going to bring up now.

263
00:25:56,754 --> 00:26:00,656
[SPEAKER_12]: I just want to address the framework that

264
00:26:02,738 --> 00:26:22,098
[SPEAKER_12]: You vice president bears brought up about dividing the ordinance into three ordinances Which You know, I don't have an opinion one way or the other on doing that but I think that there might if you do that be a fourth ordinance and and

265
00:26:23,192 --> 00:26:34,569
[SPEAKER_12]: In the works or a second part of one of those ordinances, which is regulating the tree services and arborists that cut down trees.

266
00:26:35,831 --> 00:26:36,632
[SPEAKER_12]: If I want to

267
00:26:39,072 --> 00:26:52,219
[SPEAKER_12]: But in addition on my house, if I want to change out the electrical work, I need to call a licensed contractor and they need to get a permit.

268
00:26:52,920 --> 00:27:02,125
[SPEAKER_12]: And I think that ensuring that tree work is done with the same care and professionalism and insurance is critical.

269
00:27:03,345 --> 00:27:05,487
[SPEAKER_12]: So that I guess could be part of

270
00:27:06,448 --> 00:27:11,733
[SPEAKER_12]: the private lot ordinance or could be a fourth ordinance.

271
00:27:12,714 --> 00:27:13,494
[SPEAKER_12]: Thank you very much.

272
00:27:15,556 --> 00:27:17,178
[SPEAKER_16]: Thank you, Mr. Ingber.

273
00:27:17,218 --> 00:27:18,459
[SPEAKER_16]: That's helpful.

274
00:27:18,879 --> 00:27:20,100
[SPEAKER_16]: President Morrell, you still have your hand up.

275
00:27:22,162 --> 00:27:22,863
[SPEAKER_08]: Sorry, I'll put it down.

276
00:27:24,084 --> 00:27:24,284
[SPEAKER_16]: Great.

277
00:27:25,685 --> 00:27:27,967
[SPEAKER_16]: Actually, to Barry's point,

278
00:27:30,034 --> 00:27:38,238
[SPEAKER_16]: Aggie or Tim, do we currently regulate the arborists who are, you know, tree companies who work in the city in any way?

279
00:27:42,499 --> 00:27:42,659
[SPEAKER_16]: No.

280
00:27:43,560 --> 00:27:43,820
[SPEAKER_16]: Okay.

281
00:27:43,920 --> 00:27:45,401
[SPEAKER_16]: And we don't require a permit.

282
00:27:46,241 --> 00:27:55,845
[SPEAKER_16]: Obviously there's a process through chapter 87 for a public shade tree, but for a private company, they don't have to have a permit or anything to come in and do work on a private tree or tree on private property.

283
00:27:59,451 --> 00:27:59,711
[SPEAKER_16]: Okay.

284
00:27:59,951 --> 00:28:02,273
[SPEAKER_14]: All right.

285
00:28:02,953 --> 00:28:03,414
[SPEAKER_16]: Thank you.

286
00:28:05,675 --> 00:28:08,777
[SPEAKER_16]: Any other comments from members of the council at this time?

287
00:28:10,998 --> 00:28:11,659
[SPEAKER_16]: Councilor Collins.

288
00:28:13,080 --> 00:28:14,020
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Vice President Behrs.

289
00:28:14,220 --> 00:28:17,863
[SPEAKER_07]: And thanks to everybody who's commented and thank you for the city staff for being here.

290
00:28:20,084 --> 00:28:23,707
[SPEAKER_07]: My comments are more about, you know, where do we go from here and just my perspective on that.

291
00:28:23,807 --> 00:28:25,708
[SPEAKER_07]: I think that, you know,

292
00:28:27,166 --> 00:28:30,288
[SPEAKER_07]: this is an opportunity to make what progress we can.

293
00:28:30,308 --> 00:28:47,637
[SPEAKER_07]: I think that the most organized way forward is indeed to break this up into, it looks to me probably three ordinances and move forward on those at the pace that we can, giving the legal resources and staff capacity that we have to work with.

294
00:28:47,957 --> 00:28:52,220
[SPEAKER_07]: I think that we should strengthen the protections of public shade trees,

295
00:28:53,180 --> 00:28:55,701
[SPEAKER_07]: where we can through amending that existing ordinance.

296
00:28:56,401 --> 00:29:12,426
[SPEAKER_07]: I think that we should protect existing trees and maximally encourage tree planting on private lots in the most targeted way possible to try to do the maximum amount of good, you know, probably through performance standards and site plan review for large developments as part of the zoning recodification process.

297
00:29:13,466 --> 00:29:19,290
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't love saying that because it feels like deferring it towards a process that we haven't begun yet, but I think that does make the most sense.

298
00:29:20,991 --> 00:29:23,192
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm also fine with creating a tree committee.

299
00:29:23,212 --> 00:29:36,840
[SPEAKER_07]: I think that my hesitation there is the same hesitation I have whenever we're talking about creating a new border commission, which is that I really don't love the idea of ascribing a lot of high capacity, fairly technical work to an unpaid body.

300
00:29:36,880 --> 00:29:40,362
[SPEAKER_07]: I know that we don't have a lot of money to throw towards stipends, but I think that

301
00:29:41,646 --> 00:29:46,008
[SPEAKER_07]: you know, the efficacy of that, how realistic that is really does give me pause.

302
00:29:46,048 --> 00:29:56,792
[SPEAKER_07]: And I think that this is more of a general comment, but I like to make every time we're talking about boards and commissions, I think that we're not going to achieve diversity and parity on any of our boards and commissions until we start offering compensation.

303
00:29:56,852 --> 00:30:08,656
[SPEAKER_07]: So I think that having a tree committee in general is good, but I also like to insert wherever I can, that I think that that needs to be overhauled as soon as we have the resources to do so, boards and commissions processes in general.

304
00:30:09,196 --> 00:30:09,877
[SPEAKER_07]: So I'll,

305
00:30:11,012 --> 00:30:12,592
[SPEAKER_07]: I'll end on that sidebar, thank you.

306
00:30:13,113 --> 00:30:19,934
[SPEAKER_16]: Great, we do have a couple more members of the public, and then maybe we could go into conversation about next steps.

307
00:30:19,974 --> 00:30:25,956
[SPEAKER_16]: And I'm noting that we've kind of talked about next steps throughout, but I think we should have an explicit conversation about it.

308
00:30:27,456 --> 00:30:32,698
[SPEAKER_16]: I saw Amanda Bowen on Zoom, but...

309
00:30:34,006 --> 00:30:35,406
[SPEAKER_16]: Amanda has now gone.

310
00:30:36,126 --> 00:30:41,468
[SPEAKER_16]: I do see we had one person in the chamber, and then I'll go to you, Kathy.

311
00:30:42,208 --> 00:30:44,208
[SPEAKER_16]: But name and address for the record, please.

312
00:30:44,228 --> 00:30:47,509
[SPEAKER_09]: Good evening, thank you, Vice President Behrs.

313
00:30:47,589 --> 00:30:49,670
[SPEAKER_09]: I'm Gaston Fiore, 61 Stickney Road.

314
00:30:49,690 --> 00:30:56,691
[SPEAKER_09]: I'm also a member of the Med for Energy and Environment Committee, the Med for Bicycle Advisory Commission.

315
00:30:57,311 --> 00:31:03,593
[SPEAKER_09]: However, all the thoughts that I'm gonna say are just my own and do not represent those of any other person or committees I belong to.

316
00:31:05,749 --> 00:31:15,473
[SPEAKER_09]: I just want to say that I do believe that people owning a house and living in it should pay no tax to remove any trees from the private property.

317
00:31:17,133 --> 00:31:23,716
[SPEAKER_09]: Note that developers buying existing houses would still have to pay a tax as they would not live there.

318
00:31:23,896 --> 00:31:30,579
[SPEAKER_09]: So we should be able to determine whether someone is buying a house and goes to live there or someone is buying a house to flip it over and resell it.

319
00:31:32,183 --> 00:31:43,291
[SPEAKER_09]: One of the people pushing for the ordinance said during the Medford Energy and Environment Committee September meeting the following, begin quote, I have problems with the rights of individual land owners.

320
00:31:43,731 --> 00:31:47,034
[SPEAKER_09]: Being a socialist in the first place, I don't believe that people have rights over land.

321
00:31:47,454 --> 00:31:51,277
[SPEAKER_09]: I think that there's not really any such thing as owning real property, end quote.

322
00:31:52,377 --> 00:31:58,282
[SPEAKER_09]: So I ask, is believing that people don't have rights over land is thought that is shared by the majority of Medford residents?

323
00:32:00,384 --> 00:32:08,948
[SPEAKER_09]: have there been any large-scale outreach campaigns to make residents aware of the huge tax that they're gonna have to pay whenever they remove a tree from their private property?

324
00:32:10,809 --> 00:32:18,032
[SPEAKER_09]: Elected officials should govern for all residents in Medford, not only for those that voted for them, at least for a small number with radical views.

325
00:32:19,433 --> 00:32:28,997
[SPEAKER_09]: Medford residents with trees giving shade to their house's roof, who decided to remove those trees to install solar panels, may not be able to pay the huge removal tax, and as a result, desist from going solar.

326
00:32:30,160 --> 00:32:34,223
[SPEAKER_09]: The electricity not produced by those rooftop panels will need to be produced somewhere else.

327
00:32:34,824 --> 00:32:43,411
[SPEAKER_09]: Placing an electricity generation far away from electricity consumers can lead to clearing forests and largest bodies of trees with even greater adverse environmental impacts.

328
00:32:43,795 --> 00:32:45,576
[SPEAKER_09]: than cutting a few trees in cities.

329
00:32:46,997 --> 00:32:55,801
[SPEAKER_09]: I should mention that I did send a link to document with citations for all of this to all the city councilors and anyone that would like it, I will be happy to send it.

330
00:32:55,881 --> 00:32:56,502
[SPEAKER_09]: I'm almost done.

331
00:32:57,602 --> 00:33:03,626
[SPEAKER_09]: So Medford should launch a massive educational campaign to teach residents about the diverse positive impacts of trees.

332
00:33:04,266 --> 00:33:09,749
[SPEAKER_09]: This go beyond increasing resilience to climate change, supporting wildlife and improving the aesthetics of places.

333
00:33:10,229 --> 00:33:13,371
[SPEAKER_09]: Handsome trees can also raise the sales price of a house.

334
00:33:15,004 --> 00:33:19,828
[SPEAKER_09]: Educational efforts can decrease the number of residents who ever consider tree removal from their property.

335
00:33:20,768 --> 00:33:31,176
[SPEAKER_09]: In conclusion, the proposed MET for tree ordinance encroaches too far on the rights of individual landowners by imposing a tree removal tax on residents owning their house and living in it.

336
00:33:33,273 --> 00:33:50,027
[SPEAKER_09]: In addition, the trioleum fails to account for and makes it harder to exploit local roots of solar energy contributing to shift electricity generation elsewhere with the potential to nullify or even revert the positive environmental impact that this is striving to achieve.

337
00:33:51,108 --> 00:33:51,488
[SPEAKER_09]: That's it.

338
00:33:52,249 --> 00:33:52,809
[SPEAKER_09]: Thank you very much.

339
00:33:53,109 --> 00:33:53,450
[SPEAKER_16]: Thank you.

340
00:33:53,470 --> 00:33:53,710
[SPEAKER_16]: Yeah.

341
00:33:53,850 --> 00:33:54,951
[SPEAKER_16]: And just to your comments,

342
00:33:57,092 --> 00:34:00,295
[SPEAKER_16]: It's a deliberative process to balance interests.

343
00:34:00,315 --> 00:34:18,951
[SPEAKER_16]: The draft before you, I could guarantee you is not gonna be the draft that comes out at the end of the process and comments like yours, as well as the comments of everyone here in this meeting, help us to work through the process and craft the ordinance to be as beneficial as possible for the community.

344
00:34:19,032 --> 00:34:21,394
[SPEAKER_16]: So thank you and I appreciate your comments.

345
00:34:24,638 --> 00:34:27,160
[SPEAKER_16]: I'm gonna go to one more person in public, and then can I go to you?

346
00:34:27,400 --> 00:34:27,680
[SPEAKER_16]: Thanks.

347
00:34:28,420 --> 00:34:30,841
[SPEAKER_16]: Kathy, please, I'm gonna unmute you.

348
00:34:30,861 --> 00:34:32,982
[SPEAKER_16]: Please give your name and address for the record.

349
00:34:38,104 --> 00:34:42,146
[SPEAKER_00]: Hi, my name is Kathy Bull, 27 Monument Street.

350
00:34:44,767 --> 00:34:53,191
[SPEAKER_00]: I support the ordinance, the proposed ordinance, and it sounds like it'll get probably even better in this process.

351
00:34:55,320 --> 00:35:11,104
[SPEAKER_00]: I have watched developers in our neighborhood take down trees often as a first step when they approach land that they're going to develop or to take down a house to develop that in a new way.

352
00:35:12,724 --> 00:35:22,847
[SPEAKER_00]: So I don't know if there's, if it should be, you know, written separately for different types of homeowners, whether like the previous speaker said,

353
00:35:23,782 --> 00:35:26,903
[SPEAKER_00]: something more targeted.

354
00:35:27,303 --> 00:35:28,363
[SPEAKER_00]: I'm not sure about that.

355
00:35:28,383 --> 00:35:29,243
[SPEAKER_00]: It's just a thought.

356
00:35:29,803 --> 00:35:49,047
[SPEAKER_00]: And I do think as far as what the, you know, kind of reaction to the idea of entering private property to have some governance over trees, it is a new idea in our community.

357
00:35:49,347 --> 00:35:50,127
[SPEAKER_00]: And so I think

358
00:35:51,238 --> 00:36:01,126
[SPEAKER_00]: It sounds maybe scary to some people at first, but I think in the ordinance, even as it is, there's quite a bit of flexibility about what a homeowner can do.

359
00:36:02,667 --> 00:36:04,428
[SPEAKER_00]: It's not draconian.

360
00:36:05,029 --> 00:36:10,993
[SPEAKER_00]: So I think part of it is like the previous speaker said, education.

361
00:36:11,013 --> 00:36:19,620
[SPEAKER_00]: I think climate change certainly highlights our need for a

362
00:36:21,243 --> 00:36:24,845
[SPEAKER_00]: for an abundance of canopy of trees.

363
00:36:26,146 --> 00:36:38,515
[SPEAKER_00]: And I think we just need to keep that in mind because that impacts all of us and we all can contribute to that.

364
00:36:39,435 --> 00:36:49,402
[SPEAKER_00]: So I applaud you all for the effort you've made to develop this ordinance to this point and your commitment to continuing with it, thank you.

365
00:36:51,520 --> 00:36:52,781
[SPEAKER_16]: Thank you, Kathy.

366
00:36:55,002 --> 00:36:58,444
[SPEAKER_16]: Councilor Kerrio, two more people on public participation, but do you want to, okay.

367
00:36:59,025 --> 00:37:00,586
[SPEAKER_16]: We'll go to Sarah and then Tom.

368
00:37:00,646 --> 00:37:03,067
[SPEAKER_16]: Sarah, I'm going to unmute you, name and address for the record, please.

369
00:37:05,489 --> 00:37:06,910
[SPEAKER_06]: My name is Sarah Gerald.

370
00:37:07,350 --> 00:37:09,391
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm at 29 Burbank road.

371
00:37:10,512 --> 00:37:18,337
[SPEAKER_06]: I appreciate all of the comments of many of the people who have supported the audience of the ordinance and

372
00:37:18,958 --> 00:37:23,879
[SPEAKER_06]: the work that we at Trees Medford have done to write that ordinance.

373
00:37:25,679 --> 00:37:30,560
[SPEAKER_06]: It is a work that we consider very important for this city.

374
00:37:31,900 --> 00:37:38,861
[SPEAKER_06]: Important because it goes directly to the way that climate is going to impact all of us.

375
00:37:39,702 --> 00:37:47,003
[SPEAKER_06]: If everyone were to cut down all their trees for the purposes of even

376
00:37:49,195 --> 00:38:01,383
[SPEAKER_06]: putting solar on their houses, we would all be worse off because our environment would be a lot hotter and everybody would have to pay the price of that heat.

377
00:38:03,145 --> 00:38:07,908
[SPEAKER_06]: Even, and especially those who can't afford air conditioning.

378
00:38:08,828 --> 00:38:13,912
[SPEAKER_06]: So I think trees are a resource that help us all.

379
00:38:14,646 --> 00:38:17,087
[SPEAKER_06]: They help us all to keep our houses cooler.

380
00:38:17,688 --> 00:38:24,231
[SPEAKER_06]: They help us maintain our mental equilibrium, if you will.

381
00:38:25,292 --> 00:38:30,915
[SPEAKER_06]: They provide homes for wildlife, birds that delight us.

382
00:38:31,415 --> 00:38:44,022
[SPEAKER_06]: They provide so many services, ecosystem services for hydrology in this city that I think we can't afford to just

383
00:38:45,337 --> 00:38:56,803
[SPEAKER_06]: look the other way when people take vast numbers of trees down, even if it is on their own private property, because that impacts us all.

384
00:38:57,524 --> 00:38:59,865
[SPEAKER_06]: It doesn't just impact them.

385
00:39:01,246 --> 00:39:05,508
[SPEAKER_06]: It is attacks that they are imposing on us, in effect.

386
00:39:07,129 --> 00:39:14,633
[SPEAKER_06]: And I think that, as the previous speaker said, we have a lot of, we've built in a lot of

387
00:39:16,643 --> 00:39:28,571
[SPEAKER_06]: options for maintaining the canopy that we have in Medford that we should be considering and implementing.

388
00:39:29,852 --> 00:39:31,753
[SPEAKER_06]: And that's all I have to say.

389
00:39:31,773 --> 00:39:32,874
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you very much.

390
00:39:32,894 --> 00:39:35,936
[SPEAKER_16]: Thank you, Sarah.

391
00:39:36,577 --> 00:39:38,178
[SPEAKER_16]: Next, I'm gonna go back to Tom.

392
00:39:38,238 --> 00:39:41,140
[SPEAKER_16]: If you could just give your name and address again, Tom.

393
00:39:43,628 --> 00:39:46,650
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah, I'm sorry, I didn't mean to take too many bites at the apple here.

394
00:39:47,211 --> 00:39:49,193
[SPEAKER_02]: Tom Lincoln, 27 Gleason Street.

395
00:39:49,733 --> 00:40:04,465
[SPEAKER_02]: It occurs to me, and maybe you've done this already, that there's some sort of hierarchical list in terms of benefits, and to make a bad pun here in terms of low-hanging fruit, in terms of the ordinance.

396
00:40:05,406 --> 00:40:10,570
[SPEAKER_02]: In other words, if you take, I'll just make up something here, if you take new developments,

397
00:40:11,800 --> 00:40:15,661
[SPEAKER_02]: commercial developments and say, what's the potential for increasing trees there?

398
00:40:16,021 --> 00:40:19,142
[SPEAKER_02]: What's the potential for, you know, controlling that?

399
00:40:19,602 --> 00:40:23,243
[SPEAKER_02]: And what's the aggregate effect going to be on this?

400
00:40:24,343 --> 00:40:39,207
[SPEAKER_02]: And then, you know, do the same sort of analysis and other, you know, the cemetery, for example, the Brooks Estate and, you know, any open space that the city controls, you know, is certainly in one category.

401
00:40:39,407 --> 00:40:39,607
[SPEAKER_02]: I mean,

402
00:40:41,507 --> 00:40:42,688
[SPEAKER_02]: Some things are very visible.

403
00:40:42,708 --> 00:40:51,810
[SPEAKER_02]: A lot of people are upset by the number of large trees that get chopped down, as somebody mentioned earlier, as the first step in any sort of redevelopment.

404
00:40:52,151 --> 00:40:59,493
[SPEAKER_02]: You think people could design around trees, but I guess it's cheaper just to cut them down and then build on a blank slate.

405
00:41:01,053 --> 00:41:08,556
[SPEAKER_02]: So I think there's some opportunities there for, there's some carrots here as well as some sticks, to use a bad metaphor.

406
00:41:09,662 --> 00:41:11,163
[SPEAKER_02]: for this whole thing.

407
00:41:11,183 --> 00:41:23,428
[SPEAKER_02]: Because I think at the end of the day, we want to be in a position as a community where we're protecting what we have, what we're improving, you know, so we're not losing the battle, so to speak.

408
00:41:23,949 --> 00:41:26,230
[SPEAKER_02]: We're improving the canopy.

409
00:41:26,950 --> 00:41:35,934
[SPEAKER_02]: We're making some people, you know, we're trying to make, give some incentives here, perhaps through the zoning, through the development, through design.

410
00:41:36,194 --> 00:41:37,875
[SPEAKER_02]: We don't even have design review in Medford,

411
00:41:38,677 --> 00:41:49,447
[SPEAKER_02]: a terrible thing, I dare say, to have people kind of think more about this as part of the process of development.

412
00:41:49,868 --> 00:42:00,778
[SPEAKER_02]: Because I think this is the kind of thing that at the end of the day, success is going to be made up of lots of little pieces and some big pieces all put together in some large aggregate.

413
00:42:03,707 --> 00:42:04,567
[SPEAKER_16]: Thank you, Mr. Lincoln.

414
00:42:04,587 --> 00:42:12,309
[SPEAKER_16]: We'll go to Barry, and then anyone else, please raise your hand if you would like to speak.

415
00:42:16,809 --> 00:42:22,550
[SPEAKER_12]: Barry Ingber, Driper Street, and I'm getting weird messages here.

416
00:42:23,271 --> 00:42:27,111
[SPEAKER_12]: Just two very brief responses to comments that were made.

417
00:42:28,531 --> 00:42:30,352
[SPEAKER_12]: One, the notion of

418
00:42:33,622 --> 00:42:51,574
[SPEAKER_12]: of having dominion over your own property in terms of trees is not really that different than the argument made by people who want to be able to dump toxic waste on their land or drain wetlands.

419
00:42:52,334 --> 00:42:58,779
[SPEAKER_12]: We understand that the environmental impacts of those actions go beyond the

420
00:42:59,824 --> 00:43:01,405
[SPEAKER_12]: the borders of one's property.

421
00:43:01,746 --> 00:43:03,447
[SPEAKER_12]: And so we regulate those things.

422
00:43:04,488 --> 00:43:09,351
[SPEAKER_12]: And we're here saying that trees fall into that same category.

423
00:43:11,152 --> 00:43:25,842
[SPEAKER_12]: The comment that homeowners might be taken unaware by this and you need a massive education campaign in order to make sure that people don't make mistakes and get unfairly taxed.

424
00:43:28,243 --> 00:43:44,642
[SPEAKER_12]: is an interesting one, but I think the idea is that if we do regulate tree service companies and arborists, then it's the same as the fact that I haven't a clue what has to be done when you change an electrical system.

425
00:43:45,277 --> 00:43:52,302
[SPEAKER_12]: I hire an electrician and they are responsible for pulling a permit for knowing the rules and for keeping me safe.

426
00:43:53,302 --> 00:43:57,765
[SPEAKER_12]: And I think that if we regulate arborists, we'll be doing the same thing.

427
00:43:57,845 --> 00:44:06,631
[SPEAKER_12]: Homeowners won't be unaware cutting down trees illegally because the arborists won't be allowed to do that and wouldn't do that.

428
00:44:07,551 --> 00:44:08,272
[SPEAKER_12]: Thank you very much.

429
00:44:09,338 --> 00:44:10,058
[SPEAKER_16]: Thank you, Mr. Amber.

430
00:44:10,338 --> 00:44:11,839
[SPEAKER_16]: I see both of you.

431
00:44:11,859 --> 00:44:15,040
[SPEAKER_16]: Mr. Furrier, you can come first and then you can come up after.

432
00:44:15,920 --> 00:44:21,202
[SPEAKER_09]: I just want to clarify what Barry was referring to.

433
00:44:21,262 --> 00:44:22,543
[SPEAKER_09]: I think there's a misunderstanding.

434
00:44:22,603 --> 00:44:27,464
[SPEAKER_09]: So what I was trying to say is that I'm guessing that

435
00:44:29,705 --> 00:44:36,147
[SPEAKER_09]: members of the public are for the most part not aware that there's a tree ordinance that is being discussed.

436
00:44:37,807 --> 00:44:52,292
[SPEAKER_09]: So that's why I was saying that there should be some sort of outreach campaign to make residents aware of what we are discussing here and how a tree ordinance might impact their private property.

437
00:44:54,473 --> 00:45:02,214
[SPEAKER_09]: One thing that I've mentioned in the document that I sent is that, for example, a referendum.

438
00:45:02,595 --> 00:45:03,097
[SPEAKER_09]: So I think

439
00:45:03,920 --> 00:45:26,013
[SPEAKER_09]: If the decision is to have no exemption for residents that are homeowners and live in their houses, then it sounds personally fair to me to have a referendum on the issue and let Medford residents decide whether that's something that they want or they don't want.

440
00:45:26,553 --> 00:45:35,763
[SPEAKER_09]: And then, in fact, if we do things properly, then we should also have quorum for the referendum, so meaning we should have greater than 50% participation rate, which is what happens in some European countries.

441
00:45:37,084 --> 00:45:44,972
[SPEAKER_09]: So that's what I was referring to with the large outreach campaign, is to make people aware that

442
00:45:45,893 --> 00:45:59,897
[SPEAKER_09]: you know, what's happening and the potential that they're gonna have to have a new, very large tax whenever they remove a tree from the property, something that they have never seen, they're not expecting, and they're not even thinking about.

443
00:45:59,917 --> 00:46:01,797
[SPEAKER_09]: I just wanted to clarify that.

444
00:46:02,277 --> 00:46:02,677
[SPEAKER_09]: Thank you.

445
00:46:02,717 --> 00:46:03,037
[SPEAKER_09]: Thank you.

446
00:46:04,998 --> 00:46:07,719
[SPEAKER_16]: Come up to the podium and just provide your name and address for the record, please.

447
00:46:09,339 --> 00:46:11,820
[SPEAKER_10]: Hi, Peter Nersassy on 47 Alston Street.

448
00:46:13,893 --> 00:46:23,311
[SPEAKER_10]: And I'm here because I think it's, I just want to reiterate the importance of both the public and private pieces of this because there are people.

449
00:46:25,167 --> 00:46:48,015
[SPEAKER_10]: in Medford that are dependent on the value of the tree canopy, of the tree abundance that are not property owners and are at the mercy of either the city or property owners to have that asset, to have that necessity of our urban environment.

450
00:46:49,119 --> 00:46:50,520
[SPEAKER_10]: I live on Alston Street.

451
00:46:50,580 --> 00:46:57,765
[SPEAKER_10]: As I said, our street was, when I moved there in 2010, a lush green space.

452
00:46:57,785 --> 00:46:59,226
[SPEAKER_10]: It was like a tunnel of green.

453
00:47:01,387 --> 00:47:10,633
[SPEAKER_10]: Since then, on my side of the street, which has four houses, and one of which I'm a renter, and there are a lot of renters on that block,

454
00:47:12,213 --> 00:47:25,570
[SPEAKER_10]: The three of those four houses on my side of the street have have taken down their largest tree and then I'm saying largest by far in during that time also there were six street trees on the block.

455
00:47:27,761 --> 00:47:34,425
[SPEAKER_10]: By the time the street was reconstructed over the process of a year, I'm not even sure if it doesn't seem like it's even done yet.

456
00:47:34,545 --> 00:47:37,947
[SPEAKER_10]: But those trees, there were two left.

457
00:47:38,927 --> 00:47:43,710
[SPEAKER_10]: And when the street was reconstructed, all of the street pits were paved over, filled in.

458
00:47:44,610 --> 00:47:46,692
[SPEAKER_10]: not a word as to future plans.

459
00:47:46,732 --> 00:47:48,013
[SPEAKER_10]: I've asked several times.

460
00:47:49,134 --> 00:47:51,135
[SPEAKER_10]: It doesn't seem like there was a plan going in.

461
00:47:51,676 --> 00:48:09,930
[SPEAKER_10]: As I said, we are at the mercy of the city on one hand, on all the departments, whether it's public works, whether it's engineering, whether it's the tree warden, who's clearly asked more of than is even possible in keeping up with tree removal.

462
00:48:10,750 --> 00:48:14,940
[SPEAKER_10]: Um, but on the other hand, we're also at the mercy of private property owners.

463
00:48:14,980 --> 00:48:18,889
[SPEAKER_10]: Now, this isn't just about me and my street, but

464
00:48:19,948 --> 00:48:23,089
[SPEAKER_10]: Anybody that walks down it, we have the Brooks School on my block.

465
00:48:23,149 --> 00:48:26,230
[SPEAKER_10]: We have a senior housing facility at the end of the block.

466
00:48:26,270 --> 00:48:27,430
[SPEAKER_10]: We have a church at the end of the block.

467
00:48:27,910 --> 00:48:29,051
[SPEAKER_10]: We have disabled people.

468
00:48:29,071 --> 00:48:33,552
[SPEAKER_10]: We have elderly people walking out in these sunbaked sidewalks.

469
00:48:34,072 --> 00:48:35,312
[SPEAKER_10]: I walk all over town.

470
00:48:35,432 --> 00:48:36,573
[SPEAKER_10]: I run all over town.

471
00:48:36,593 --> 00:48:46,495
[SPEAKER_10]: There are places you can't even, in a summer where we've had more 90 plus degrees days than you can imagine, there's just no shelter.

472
00:48:46,755 --> 00:48:48,076
[SPEAKER_10]: As one of the commenters mentioned,

473
00:48:49,016 --> 00:48:58,602
[SPEAKER_10]: It's an energy issue at this point where we're cooling our houses because we've failed to protect them from the heat.

474
00:48:59,422 --> 00:49:04,365
[SPEAKER_10]: We've definitely failed to protect pedestrians, just people out in neighborhoods.

475
00:49:06,186 --> 00:49:09,768
[SPEAKER_10]: There are places where that's going to come down to private landowners.

476
00:49:09,848 --> 00:49:12,969
[SPEAKER_10]: Private landowners are going to provide that where the city can.

477
00:49:13,829 --> 00:49:27,515
[SPEAKER_10]: I don't know how this is going to apply to the city's backup sidewalk program, where I know that there's a way for individual landowners to get a city tree placed in their property.

478
00:49:27,856 --> 00:49:32,257
[SPEAKER_10]: Is that going to be treated as a private tree or is that going to be treated as a public tree?

479
00:49:32,918 --> 00:49:35,239
[SPEAKER_10]: I mean, that's a question that's out there.

480
00:49:36,223 --> 00:49:44,409
[SPEAKER_10]: Anyway, I don't wanna go on and on, but it is very important to a lot of stakeholders in Medford that we have both components and they both be strong.

481
00:49:45,009 --> 00:49:45,370
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you.

482
00:49:46,110 --> 00:49:46,570
[SPEAKER_16]: Thank you.

483
00:49:47,971 --> 00:49:50,973
[SPEAKER_16]: One more person, then I'll get to you Councilor Kerrio.

484
00:49:51,474 --> 00:49:54,856
[SPEAKER_16]: I think it's just best that we do the public at once.

485
00:49:55,397 --> 00:49:58,279
[SPEAKER_16]: Go to Sarah and then Councilor Kerrio and then President Rhoads.

486
00:49:58,339 --> 00:49:58,679
[SPEAKER_16]: Sarah.

487
00:49:59,900 --> 00:50:04,303
[SPEAKER_06]: I would just, I know that this process takes some time,

488
00:50:05,108 --> 00:50:14,777
[SPEAKER_06]: Um, and I know that I and many of the people who have spoken today are very serious about the needs to maintain our tree canopy.

489
00:50:16,059 --> 00:50:20,343
[SPEAKER_06]: And I would encourage you to develop a moratorium

490
00:50:21,831 --> 00:50:27,935
[SPEAKER_06]: so that we can maintain what we can while this process goes through.

491
00:50:29,176 --> 00:50:42,907
[SPEAKER_06]: Many people are interested in this and want to make sure this goes through as soon as it can go through, but it's going to take some time and there are some thorny issues to resolve.

492
00:50:44,128 --> 00:50:58,652
[SPEAKER_06]: And so I would encourage you to develop a short ordinance related to a moratorium so that we can, so that you have the time to do the work that you need to do.

493
00:51:01,093 --> 00:51:01,473
[SPEAKER_16]: Thank you.

494
00:51:01,493 --> 00:51:02,934
[SPEAKER_16]: Councilor Caviello.

495
00:51:02,954 --> 00:51:03,614
[SPEAKER_01]: Thank you, Mr. President.

496
00:51:04,875 --> 00:51:06,416
[SPEAKER_01]: The gentleman just spoke a few minutes ago.

497
00:51:06,456 --> 00:51:08,697
[SPEAKER_01]: We do have a back of the law tree.

498
00:51:08,717 --> 00:51:10,437
[SPEAKER_01]: I think Aggie can explain to you.

499
00:51:11,118 --> 00:51:13,519
[SPEAKER_01]: A lot of people don't take advantage of it.

500
00:51:13,599 --> 00:51:16,180
[SPEAKER_01]: I think it's a good program for people like trees.

501
00:51:16,200 --> 00:51:25,604
[SPEAKER_01]: But when you see private homes taking down trees, usually it's not a decision made lightly.

502
00:51:25,624 --> 00:51:31,207
[SPEAKER_01]: A lot of those trees get taken down because they're diseased or there's some reason to it.

503
00:51:31,607 --> 00:51:34,188
[SPEAKER_01]: And the decision to cut down a tree is quite costly.

504
00:51:36,135 --> 00:51:43,178
[SPEAKER_01]: If you ever cut a tree down on your own property, you're looking at three, $4,000 just to cut the tree down, nevermind getting the stump out of there.

505
00:51:43,538 --> 00:51:49,540
[SPEAKER_01]: So when people cut, it's not a decision that you just, hey, just cut the tree down.

506
00:51:49,600 --> 00:51:54,762
[SPEAKER_01]: It's quite expensive and usually it's cut down for a reason.

507
00:51:55,122 --> 00:51:57,142
[SPEAKER_01]: Private properties just don't cut down trees.

508
00:51:57,202 --> 00:51:58,763
[SPEAKER_01]: I mean, I'm not talking about development.

509
00:51:59,583 --> 00:52:01,763
[SPEAKER_01]: But private homeowners are pretty responsible.

510
00:52:02,244 --> 00:52:04,284
[SPEAKER_01]: And they're not cutting trees down just to say they're cutting it down.

511
00:52:04,564 --> 00:52:07,064
[SPEAKER_01]: They're cutting it down because they're old and they're diseased.

512
00:52:07,224 --> 00:52:09,705
[SPEAKER_01]: And let's say it is quite expensive to do that.

513
00:52:09,725 --> 00:52:18,286
[SPEAKER_01]: But, you know, the city of Memphis is an old community and we have a lot of old trees.

514
00:52:19,147 --> 00:52:26,568
[SPEAKER_01]: And I think, you know, Aggie will explain to you that, you know, we've had trees that are a hundred years old and, you know, we've had some storms where they've

515
00:52:27,360 --> 00:52:30,401
[SPEAKER_01]: they've just come down over the years too.

516
00:52:30,661 --> 00:52:33,762
[SPEAKER_01]: And we do our best to replant them.

517
00:52:33,782 --> 00:52:39,744
[SPEAKER_01]: But as you can see, I know you're shaking your head there.

518
00:52:40,264 --> 00:52:41,364
[SPEAKER_01]: We've got the stumps that we have.

519
00:52:41,384 --> 00:52:44,725
[SPEAKER_01]: We're trying to get rid of the stumps now and plant new trees where those are.

520
00:52:44,745 --> 00:52:46,306
[SPEAKER_01]: It takes time, it takes money.

521
00:52:48,507 --> 00:52:49,967
[SPEAKER_01]: It takes time, it takes money.

522
00:52:50,631 --> 00:52:51,572
[SPEAKER_01]: We do have a program.

523
00:52:51,612 --> 00:52:52,573
[SPEAKER_01]: We are doing it now.

524
00:52:53,113 --> 00:52:59,519
[SPEAKER_01]: And, you know, Tim, as you explained, you know, a lot of those people, when that stuff comes out, they're going to want a tree put back in there.

525
00:53:00,159 --> 00:53:04,623
[SPEAKER_01]: And those trees came down because, all those trees came down because of weather and storms.

526
00:53:05,524 --> 00:53:07,706
[SPEAKER_01]: They weren't just chopped down for no reason.

527
00:53:07,746 --> 00:53:08,847
[SPEAKER_01]: They were taken down for a reason.

528
00:53:09,367 --> 00:53:13,831
[SPEAKER_01]: So we are, you know, I know we're not on a pace that anyone would like, but

529
00:53:17,592 --> 00:53:19,615
[SPEAKER_01]: The trees that were taken down were taken down for a reason.

530
00:53:19,855 --> 00:53:22,758
[SPEAKER_01]: They weren't just taken down because we were being irresponsible.

531
00:53:25,376 --> 00:53:27,998
[SPEAKER_01]: No, but people think that we're just cutting down trees.

532
00:53:28,318 --> 00:53:34,503
[SPEAKER_01]: And let's say, yes, you have developers in the community that are irresponsible and just shave down trees.

533
00:53:34,764 --> 00:53:36,105
[SPEAKER_01]: And I don't think that's right either.

534
00:53:36,545 --> 00:53:39,688
[SPEAKER_01]: So I'm all in favor of, I live right down the street from you.

535
00:53:39,768 --> 00:53:42,550
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm in favor of all the trees we can put in.

536
00:53:43,971 --> 00:53:46,834
[SPEAKER_01]: So, but again, we're trying to catch up.

537
00:53:47,694 --> 00:53:49,336
[SPEAKER_01]: It takes time, it takes money.

538
00:53:50,196 --> 00:53:52,058
[SPEAKER_01]: And I say, you know what I say?

539
00:53:52,118 --> 00:53:54,600
[SPEAKER_01]: If you have a tree, if you have space in your house,

540
00:53:55,262 --> 00:53:56,865
[SPEAKER_01]: Talk to Aggie, she'll get you a treat in your yard.

541
00:54:05,342 --> 00:54:07,743
[SPEAKER_10]: Again, Peter Nersessian, Alston Street.

542
00:54:09,304 --> 00:54:15,906
[SPEAKER_10]: I am not saying that, I never commented on the justification of any tree being removed.

543
00:54:16,427 --> 00:54:28,152
[SPEAKER_10]: What I'm talking about is maintenance of the canopy, about being ahead of it, about having the resources in place, about having the regulations in place to make sure that we don't continue to backslide.

544
00:54:28,512 --> 00:54:30,092
[SPEAKER_10]: Because all the trees that you're talking about,

545
00:54:31,653 --> 00:54:40,799
[SPEAKER_10]: there was no storm or anything that mandated filling in six tree pits on my block, okay?

546
00:54:40,819 --> 00:54:50,845
[SPEAKER_10]: There is no, any land or any property owner that has a tree that has to be taken down, totally understandable, but there is no,

547
00:54:52,106 --> 00:54:55,851
[SPEAKER_10]: There is no mandate to maintain the tree cover that we have.

548
00:54:55,891 --> 00:54:58,094
[SPEAKER_10]: There's no replacement.

549
00:54:58,514 --> 00:55:00,637
[SPEAKER_10]: That is the issue that we're talking about here.

550
00:55:00,677 --> 00:55:05,943
[SPEAKER_10]: We're not talking about not cutting down diseased trees.

551
00:55:06,024 --> 00:55:08,627
[SPEAKER_10]: We have a very small tree department here.

552
00:55:08,967 --> 00:55:09,888
[SPEAKER_16]: Mr. Sena has the floor.

553
00:55:10,932 --> 00:55:15,218
[SPEAKER_16]: I don't want, I tend to run a casual meeting because I think a discussion is important.

554
00:55:15,839 --> 00:55:18,783
[SPEAKER_16]: I would ask that everyone direct their comments to me through the chair at this point.

555
00:55:18,943 --> 00:55:19,224
[SPEAKER_16]: All right.

556
00:55:19,324 --> 00:55:19,564
[SPEAKER_16]: Thank you.

557
00:55:24,768 --> 00:55:32,455
[SPEAKER_10]: As I'm not a property owner, thousands and thousands, what is it, 50% of Medford is renters, something like that.

558
00:55:33,456 --> 00:55:37,019
[SPEAKER_10]: We don't have the ability to take a tree on our property.

559
00:55:37,339 --> 00:55:45,786
[SPEAKER_10]: We're at the mercy of property owners who cut down trees for very good reasons and then don't replace them.

560
00:55:46,607 --> 00:55:47,548
[SPEAKER_10]: That's all I have to say.

