[SPEAKER_16]: Yes.

649
01:00:57,866 --> 01:00:58,487
[SPEAKER_13]: President Morrell.

650
01:00:58,867 --> 01:00:59,067
[SPEAKER_13]: Yes.

651
01:00:59,508 --> 01:01:00,249
[SPEAKER_13]: Vice President Behrs.

652
01:01:00,970 --> 01:01:04,554
[SPEAKER_16]: Yes, if I'm the affirmative, it's none in the negative two absent the motion passes.

653
01:01:06,416 --> 01:01:07,597
[SPEAKER_16]: I recognize Councilor Seng.

654
01:01:10,580 --> 01:01:11,721
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you, Vice President Behrs.

655
01:01:12,321 --> 01:01:24,588
[SPEAKER_03]: I want to let the public speak first because I think this is one of those important meetings where the public gives us their opinion and we take that into account and we fold that into the ordinance.

656
01:01:24,768 --> 01:01:29,531
[SPEAKER_03]: And so I think it was important for me to let everyone, to hear from everyone first.

657
01:01:29,551 --> 01:01:36,575
[SPEAKER_03]: I think generally there seems to be a lot of consensus around our shared goals, our overall goals.

658
01:01:37,976 --> 01:01:54,458
[SPEAKER_03]: to increase our tree canopy, which right now is below what we ideally would have, to be proactive when it comes to climate action, to separate when it comes to the technicalities of it, to separate the ordinance into different sections.

659
01:01:55,138 --> 01:02:01,960
[SPEAKER_03]: And I think there seems to be a lot of agreement around the more public property facing aspects of this ordinance.

660
01:02:02,960 --> 01:02:18,163
[SPEAKER_03]: I think we also see an important role that we have is to balance different interests, which I think city government is uniquely positioned to do given the professional staff expertise on issues like this that we see in this audience today and working in city hall.

661
01:02:18,623 --> 01:02:26,826
[SPEAKER_03]: and our roles as counselors in liaising with the public and getting feedback and transmitting that to the people writing this ordinance.

662
01:02:28,287 --> 01:02:34,329
[SPEAKER_03]: I think the importance of private property is self-evident, but I think it's also important to note that

663
01:02:35,707 --> 01:02:38,888
[SPEAKER_03]: The trees are a public good as well.

664
01:02:39,528 --> 01:02:44,230
[SPEAKER_03]: They lower surface heat in neighborhoods, the surface heat temperature in neighborhoods.

665
01:02:44,290 --> 01:02:52,813
[SPEAKER_03]: They are important for our elderly population when it comes to heat waves and the danger of heat stroke and heat fatigue.

666
01:02:53,513 --> 01:02:57,735
[SPEAKER_03]: And they can also help lower energy costs for households as well.

667
01:02:58,916 --> 01:03:08,263
[SPEAKER_03]: My personal view is that the fine is economically sound, but I'm happy to have a conversation on that.

668
01:03:09,384 --> 01:03:21,613
[SPEAKER_03]: And I also like the idea of an educational campaign that talks about how important preserving trees on people's private property is and how that can help

669
01:03:22,493 --> 01:03:33,942
[SPEAKER_03]: private property owners, but I also think that this idea underscores the need for a better communication strategy from City Hall and a more comprehensive communication strategy from City Hall as well.

670
01:03:35,283 --> 01:03:41,207
[SPEAKER_03]: We've already basically hinted at the way forward, but I mean when I do think about the way forward, I would be most comfortable

671
01:03:41,827 --> 01:03:51,218
[SPEAKER_03]: Um, if, uh, with all the, with the departments that President Morrell mentioned meeting, um, and then coming back to us for continued conversation on the details.

672
01:03:51,278 --> 01:03:57,906
[SPEAKER_03]: And I, I think, um, from what we've heard from Commissioner McGibbon, this is, this is, this would be super helpful for, um,

673
01:03:58,707 --> 01:04:03,332
[SPEAKER_03]: for all of us to get a better picture of the finances and the resources necessary for an ordinance like this.

674
01:04:03,812 --> 01:04:12,642
[SPEAKER_03]: And I think another important note is our city has ambitious plans out there on climate action, on a comprehensive plan.

675
01:04:12,682 --> 01:04:19,149
[SPEAKER_03]: And I wanna make sure that this tree ordinance aligns with our more general city plans as well.

676
01:04:20,035 --> 01:04:20,895
[SPEAKER_16]: Thank you, Councilor Sang.

677
01:04:21,916 --> 01:04:23,636
[SPEAKER_16]: There's one more hand for public participation.

678
01:04:23,656 --> 01:04:31,339
[SPEAKER_16]: And then I have a couple of comments and then requests for my colleagues to make motions, but I will go back to Martha first.

679
01:04:31,580 --> 01:04:32,040
[SPEAKER_16]: Martha.

680
01:04:32,060 --> 01:04:35,121
[SPEAKER_16]: You should be unmuted.

681
01:04:35,161 --> 01:04:37,802
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you, Councilor Behrs.

682
01:04:38,142 --> 01:04:39,483
[SPEAKER_05]: I just wanted to...

683
01:04:41,585 --> 01:04:55,398
[SPEAKER_05]: point out that the ordinance does create, does include language so that if a tree is diseased or presents a hazard, it can be removed a private tree on private property.

684
01:04:56,038 --> 01:05:05,787
[SPEAKER_05]: No one is going to be penalized because they want to take down a tree that is at the end of its life, diseased or dropping branches.

685
01:05:07,669 --> 01:05:12,413
[SPEAKER_05]: I think the fear that this would put people in that position is not warranted.

686
01:05:14,014 --> 01:05:25,203
[SPEAKER_05]: I know I see in my neighborhood, West Medford, that a lot of the tree removal is motivated by the desire to create more parking spaces.

687
01:05:27,113 --> 01:05:31,997
[SPEAKER_05]: which is probably not the best reason to take down the tree canopy.

688
01:05:32,217 --> 01:05:50,491
[SPEAKER_05]: I also wanna point out that Mayor Wu today in Boston created an urban forestry division and expanded their staff from three to 16 because trees are one of the most important technologies in the city of Boston's climate plan.

689
01:05:50,531 --> 01:05:55,675
[SPEAKER_05]: So that just reinforces the importance of maintaining tree canopy

690
01:05:56,505 --> 01:05:58,726
[SPEAKER_05]: for all of us, thank you.

691
01:06:00,147 --> 01:06:00,828
[SPEAKER_16]: Thank you, Martha.

692
01:06:01,748 --> 01:06:05,790
[SPEAKER_16]: Before I comment, any further comments from remaining members of the council?

693
01:06:06,751 --> 01:06:09,433
[SPEAKER_16]: Seeing none, just a few comments.

694
01:06:10,533 --> 01:06:23,581
[SPEAKER_16]: My first comment is that I just reviewed these communications a little more deeply and what we received back from the KP Law legal consultants was actually very literally it said,

695
01:06:24,815 --> 01:06:27,659
[SPEAKER_16]: have the departments draft this and get back to us.

696
01:06:27,699 --> 01:06:33,786
[SPEAKER_16]: I just want to confirm, do you have the capacity to draft an ordinance within your department right now?

697
01:06:33,806 --> 01:06:33,846
[SPEAKER_16]: No.

698
01:06:37,059 --> 01:06:39,901
[SPEAKER_04]: not in a timely manner like we're talking about.

699
01:06:39,982 --> 01:06:44,986
